  "text": "We next assessed whether Foxg1 can repress Tbr1 expression in vivo. We used Foxg1 Ϫ/Ϫ constitutive knock-out brains in which a loss of Foxg1 results in excessive production of the earliest-born CR cells in the cortex [CITATION_1] . As expected in these cortices, we observed Tbr1 upregulation in the CP because of its expression in CR cells ( Fig. 5BЈ; Hevner et al.,  2001 ). Therefore, we coelectroporated pCAGGS-Foxg1 with pCAGGS-GFP constructs into E14.5 Foxg1 Ϫ/Ϫ cortices and examined Tbr1 expression at E18.5 (Fig. 5A ). Foxg1 induction cellautonomously repressed Tbr1 expression within this GFP ϩ cell cluster (Fig. 5C -CЉ, compared with control pCAGGS-GFP-only transfected cells in Fig. 5B-BЉ) ; Ctip2 (Fig. 5Cٞ) and Fezf2 (Fig.  5DЈ ) expression were only induced in this Tbr1",
